name: Separate logic and UI with custom hooks and components
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Components with mixed business logic and UI rendering
then: Extract logic into custom hooks, keep components focused on UI
why: Follows enterprise best practices: separation of concerns, reusability, maintainability, and better testing.
description: Extract business logic into custom hooks (e.g., useNumberInput) and create reusable UI components (e.g., NumberInputField) to maintain clean architecture and follow enterprise-grade patterns.
description: Use custom hooks for logic, components for UI rendering

## Pattern
```tsx
// ✅ Good: Hook for logic
const useNumberInput = (value, options) => {
  // Business logic here
  return { value, onChange, onBlur, onFocus };
};

// ✅ Good: Component for UI
const NumberInputField = ({ value, onInputChange, fieldName, ...props }) => {
  const numberInput = useNumberInput(value, props);
  return <TextField {...props} {...numberInput} />;
};

// ❌ Avoid: Mixed logic and UI
const MyComponent = () => {
  const [value, setValue] = useState('');
  // Business logic mixed with UI rendering
  return <TextField onChange={...} />;
};
```

## Benefits
- Separation of concerns
- Reusable logic across components
- Easier testing and maintenance
- Professional enterprise architecture

globs: ["frontend/src/**/*.tsx"]
alwaysApply: true
---
